"A third rule is, that there should be some or- donnance, some design or little plot, which may deserve the title of a pastoral sceme. This is every where observed by Virgil, and particularly remarkable in the first Eclogue, the standard of all pastorals. A beautiful landscape presents it- self to your view; a shepherd with his flock around him, resting securely under a spreading beech, which furnished the first f√©od to our an- cestors ; another in a quite different situation of mind and circumstances; the sun setting; the hospitality of the more fortunate shepherd, &ec. And here M. Fontenelle seems not a little wanting."